## Managing Expectations

### Scope Creep
Scope creep is the enemy of every ID project. 
It starts with small additions and ends with 
a project that's twice the size of the original agreement.

Prevention:
- Document scope in writing at project kickoff
- Define what's included *and* what's excluded
- Establish a change request process for additions
- Make the cost of additions visible: 
  *"We can add that — it'll add approximately 
  two weeks to the timeline. Want me to flag 
  that for the sponsor?"*

### Timeline Expectations
Stakeholders routinely underestimate how long 
good design takes.

Educate early:
- Share a project timeline with review milestones 
  at kickoff
- Build in buffer — reviews always take longer 
  than planned
- Communicate proactively when timelines are at risk — 
  don't wait until a deadline is missed

### "Just Make It Look Nice" Requests
Stakeholders sometimes conflate production value 
with instructional value. A beautifully designed 
course that doesn't change behavior is an 
expensive failure.

Response: 
*"I want it to look great too — and I also want 
to make sure we're investing the production time 
where it'll have the most impact on learning. 
Can we talk about which sections are highest 
priority for that kind of treatment?"*

