## Pushback and Difficult Conversations

### Pushing Back on Bad Ideas
Part of the consulting role is telling stakeholders 
things they don't want to hear. Do it directly, 
respectfully, and with evidence.

**Formula:** Acknowledge → Reframe → Recommend

> *"I understand why a course feels like the right 
> answer here — it's a visible response to a real 
> problem. What I'm seeing in the data, though, 
markdown
> suggests this is less about knowledge and more 
> about [X]. A course might not move the needle 
> the way you're hoping. What if we tried [Y] instead? 
> Here's why I think it would be more effective..."*

### When You're Overruled
Sometimes stakeholders will proceed with an approach 
you don't agree with. When that happens:

- Document your recommendation and their decision
- Do your best work within the constraints you're given
- Propose a post-launch evaluation so results can 
  inform future decisions
- Don't let disagreement become adversarial — 
  your credibility for the next conversation 
  depends on how you handle this one

### Delivering Difficult Feedback on SME Content
When SME-provided content needs significant revision:

- Lead with appreciation for their expertise and time
- Frame feedback around the learner experience, 
  not your preferences: *"I want to make sure 
  this lands for someone who's brand new to this —"*
- Be specific: vague feedback ("this feels too complex") 
  is harder to act on than targeted feedback 
  ("this section covers six concepts at once — 
  can we prioritize the two most critical ones?")
- Offer solutions, not just problems

